\section{Getting started}

To play with [[acid]] and [[ratrace]], you will first need to install
the \plan fork used in \principia (see \urlinstall).
%
To trace the system calls of a program:
\begin{verbatim}
$ ratrace -c /bin/ls /dev
...
75 ls Open  6a65 0xcfffeb3/"/dev" 0x0 = 3 "" 20000135 20000136
75 ls Brk   b834 0x20c98 = 0 "" 20000138 20000139
75 ls Pread b824 3 0xfbf8 65595 -1 0xfbf8/"=.M.....
...
/dev/bintime
/dev/cons
...
75 ls Close 6a6c 3 = 0 "" 20000140 20000142
75 ls Exits 6a74 0/""
$
\end{verbatim}


To debug a program with [[acid]]:

\begin{verbatim}
$ acid /bin/ls
/bin/ls:386 plan 9 executable
/lib/acid/port.acid
/lib/acid/386.acid
acid: new()
72: system call _main      SUBL $0x48,SP
72: breakpoint  main+0x3   MOVL $bin(SB),AX
acid: stk()
main(argv=0xcfffefa4,argc=0x1)+0x3 /utilities/files/ls.c:91
_main+0x31 /libc/386/main9.s:16
acid: cont()
...
bin
boot
...
<stdin>:4 (error) msg: pid=72 startstop: process exited
acid:
\end{verbatim}


%claude:
[[acid]] is also available through both
plan9port\furl{https://9fans.github.io/plan9port/} and
Goken9cc\furl{https://github.com/aryx/goken9cc}, so you
can use it on Linux or macOS to debug native ELF binaries
compiled with gcc or clang.
%
On Linux, [[libmach]] uses
[[ptrace]] under the hood for process control, memory
access, single-stepping, and breakpoints---so the full
debugging experience works. [[acidtypes]] extracts type
information from DWARF debug sections.

\section{Requirements}

%claude:
Because this book is made of C source code, you will need
a good knowledge of the C programming language~\cite{k-r}.
%
Reading the \book{Kernel} is helpful, especially the
chapter on ``Debugging Support'': the kernel's [[/proc]]
file system is the interface through which both [[acid]]
and [[ratrace]] control and observe processes.
%
The \book{Linker} and \book{Compiler} explain how
the symbol tables and line number information that
[[acid]] reads are generated.

For background on debugger internals in general,
Rosenberg's {\em How Debuggers Work}~\cite{how-debuggers-work}
is one of the few books on the subject, covering
breakpoints, single-stepping, and symbol table
interpretation.
