\section{Abstract syntax tree}

%claude:
Like many interpreters, [[acid]] parses input into an
abstract syntax tree (AST) and then walks it to evaluate
expressions and execute statements. Each AST node is a
[<Node>] with an [[Opcode]], left and right children, and
optional extra fields for the symbol, type, and literal
value.
%
Note that nodes are garbage-collected (they embed a [<Gc>] header).

%claude:
For example, the [[acid]] expression
\begin{verbatim}
   *main + 3
\end{verbatim}
parses into the following tree:
\begin{verbatim}
                  Node{op=OADD}
                  /          \
             Node             Node{op=OCONST,
            {op=OINDM}         type=TINT, ival=3}
             /
        Node{op=ONAME,
             sym=Lsym{name="main"}}
\end{verbatim}
%
The yacc grammar rules build this tree by calling [<an()>]
bottom-up: first the [[ONAME]] leaf, then the [[OINDM]]
unary, then the [[OCONST]] for the literal, and finally the
[[OADD]] root that joins them. The interpreter ([<execute()>])
later walks the tree top-down, dispatching on each node's
opcode through the [<expop>] table.

\subsection{AST nodes: [[Node]]}

%claude:
The [[Node]] structure serves double duty: it represents
both AST nodes (during parsing and execution) and temporary
results (during expression evaluation, where [[op]] is set
to [[OCONST]] and the embedded [[Store]] union holds the
actual integer, float, string, or list value).
%
The ``value fields'' are not direct members of [[Node]]:
they live inside the embedded [[Store]] struct (added via
the kencc anonymous struct feature, see chunk
\verb+<<[[Node]] other fields>>+ below). Thanks to this
embedding, you can write [[n->ival]] or [[n->fval]] directly
on a [[Node]] just like on a [[Value]].

<<struct [[Node]]>>=
struct Node
{
    <<[[Node]] first gc field>>

    // enum<opcode>
    char	op;
    Node*	left;
    Node*	right;

    <<[[Node]] other fields>>
};
@

<<constant [[ZN]]>>=
#define ZN	(Node*)0
@

%claude:
The [<an()>] function allocates a new node and adds it to
the garbage collector's linked list.

<<function [[an]]>>=
Node*
an(int op, Node *l, Node *r)
{
    Node *n;

    n = gmalloc(sizeof(Node));
    memset(n, 0, sizeof(Node));

    <<[[an()]] add node [[n]] to [[gcl]]>>

    n->op = op;
    n->left = l;
    n->right = r;

    return n;
}
@


