\section{[[Type]] system}

%claude:
[[acid]] has a simple dynamic type system with five types:
integers, floats, strings, lists, and code (unevaluated
expressions passed by reference). Every [[acid]] value
carries a type tag that is checked at runtime during
expression evaluation.

<<enum [[_anon_ (acid/acid.h)]]2>>=
enum Type_kind
{
    TINT,
    TFLOAT,

    TSTRING,
    TLIST,

    TCODE,
};
@

%claude:
The five-type runtime [[Type_kind]] above is for [[acid]]
\emph{values}---what arithmetic and assignment operate on.
The [[Type]] struct below is something else entirely: it
describes a \emph{C-level} aggregate (a struct or union from
the program being debugged), so that [[acid]] can walk the
fields of a [[Proc]] or a [[Pgrp]] from the running kernel
and print them by name. Each [[Type]] is one row in a
field list; multiple rows are linked through [[next]] to
form the full layout of an aggregate. The interesting fields
are:
\begin{itemize}
\item [[offset]]: byte offset of this field within the
parent struct (the value the C compiler hardcoded into
[[loadword]] instructions);
\item [[fmt]]: a single-character format spec ([[X]] for
hex, [[D]] for decimal, [[s]] for string, etc.) telling
[[acid]] how to print the raw bytes;
\item [[depth]]: pointer-indirection depth, so [[fmt='X']],
[[depth=2]] means ``pointer-to-pointer-to-hex'';
\item [[type]] / [[tag]] / [[base]]: links into the
[[Lsym]] symbol table that name the field, the parent
aggregate, and (for nested aggregates) the inner type.
\end{itemize}
%
The split between value-level [[Type_kind]] and field-level
[[Type]] is what lets [[acid]] type-check its own scripting
language while still letting the user write
[[complex Proc { 'X' 0 p; 'X' 4 next; }]] and then say
[[print(*((Proc)addr).p)]] without ever rebuilding the
debugger. The C type description is data inside [[acid]],
not code.

<<struct [[Type]]>>=
struct Type
{
    Type*	next;

    int	offset;
    char	fmt;
    char	depth;

    Lsym*	type;
    Lsym*	tag;
    Lsym*	base;
};
@




\section{Runtime values}

%yoann: transition paragraph and introduce the section
%claude:
After the AST and types, we now look at the data structures
that hold actual values during execution. When [[acid]]
evaluates an expression, the result is stored in a [[Value]]
node containing both the data ([[Store]]) and a type tag.
List elements share the same [[Store]] structure so that
operations like [[append]] and [[head]] can move values
between [[Value]] and [[List]] without conversion.

\subsection{Formats}

% saw type before, format is related
% 'X' hexa, 'D' decimal, 'i' = assembly, 'a' = ?

%claude:
Each value also carries a {format} character that controls
how it is printed. Formats are orthogonal to types: an integer
can be displayed in hex, decimal, or even as a disassembled
instruction. Here are the main format characters:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{cl}
\toprule
{\bf Format} & {\bf Meaning} \\
\midrule
[['D']] & decimal integer \\
[['X']] & hexadecimal integer \\
[['o']] & octal integer \\
[['c']] & character (single byte) \\
[['C']] & rune (UTF-8 character) \\
[['b']] & byte \\
[['s']] & string \\
[['f']] & single-precision float \\
[['g']] & double-precision float \\
[['i']] & disassembled instruction \\
[['I']] & disassembled with file:line \\
[['a']] & complex/aggregate (struct) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\noindent The format characters double as {format suffixes} in the
[[acid]] language: \verb+x\D+ prints [[x]] in decimal, [[*PC\i]]
disassembles the instruction at PC, and so on.

\subsection{Runtime values: [[Value]] and [[Store]]}

%claude:
A [[Value]] is a runtime value in [[acid]]: it contains a
[[Store]] (the actual data), a type tag, and a scope pointer
for managing local variables.
%
[[Store]] is factored out as
a separate struct because it is embedded by inclusion in
both [[Value]] and [[List]] nodes---this is a kencc extension
where an anonymous struct field makes its members directly
accessible (like [[v->ival]] instead of [[v->store.ival]]).

