\subsection{Compound values: [[String]] and [[List]]}

%claude:
[[String]] and [[List]] are the two compound value types in
[[acid]]. Both are garbage-collected (they embed a [[Gc]] header).
%
[[String]] holds a length-counted byte array. 
Like [[Str]] in [[ratrace]], [[String]] uses the trick of
placing the character data right after the struct in a single
allocation---[[strnodlen()]] allocates [[sizeof(String)+len+1]]
bytes and points [[s->string]] past the struct header.

<<struct [[String]]>>=
struct String
{
    <<[[String]] first gc field>>
    char* string;
    int	  len;
};
@
%old: I renamed it to StringAcid and then typedef struct StringAcid String;
% but why? conflict on struct String with libstring? for codegraph?

<<function [[strnode]]>>=
String*
strnode(char *name)
{
    return strnodlen(name, strlen(name));
}
@

<<function [[strnodlen]]>>=
String*
strnodlen(char *name, int len)
{
    String *s;

    s = gmalloc(sizeof(String)+len+1);
    s->string = (char*)s+sizeof(String);
    s->len = len;
    if(name != 0)
        memmove(s->string, name, len);
    s->string[len] = '\0';

    <<[[strnodlen()]] add String [[s]] to [[gcl]]>>

    return s;
}
@


%\subsection{[[List]]}

[[List]] is a
singly-linked list where each node contains a [[Store]]
(so list elements can be integers, strings, or nested lists).
%
You may wonder why [[List]] embeds a [[Store]] rather than a
full [[Value]]. The reason is mostly historical: [[Value]]
also carries scope and pop fields used by the symbol table
(for shadowing in nested scopes), which are meaningless for
list elements. Embedding [[Store]] keeps [[List]] nodes small
and avoids dragging in scope-management state. The trade-off
is that the type tag has to be duplicated in [[List]] (as a
[[type]] field at the end of the struct), which is slightly
redundant with the [[fmt]] field in [[Store]]. A cleaner
design might split [[Value]] into a small core (used by both
[[List]] and the symbol table) plus a wrapper for scope
information, but the current code is small and works.


<<struct [[List]]>>=
struct List
{
    <<[[List]] first gc field>>

    Store;

    List*	next;
    // enum<Type_kind> ?
    char	type;
};
@

<<function [[al]]>>=
List*
al(int t)
{
    List *l;

    l = gmalloc(sizeof(List));
    memset(l, 0, sizeof(List));
    l->type = t;

    <<[[al()]] add List [[l]] to [[gcl]]>>

    return l;
}
@

\subsection{Garbage collector header: [[Gc]]}

% mark and sweep

%claude:
[[acid]] uses a simple {mark-and-sweep} garbage collector
for its heap-allocated objects (nodes, strings, and lists).
Every collectible object starts with a [[Gc]] header containing
a mark bit and a link pointer. All allocated objects are
chained through [[gcl]] (the GC list). During collection,
the GC first clears all marks, then scans the symbol table
to mark reachable objects, and finally sweeps the list to
free unmarked objects.

<<struct [[Gc]]>>=
struct Gc
{
    char gcmark;
    Gc*	 gclink;
};
@

<<global [[gcl]]>>=
Gc*	gcl;
@


<<[[strnodlen()]] add String [[s]] to [[gcl]]>>=
s->gclink = gcl;
gcl = s;
@
<<[[al()]] add List [[l]] to [[gcl]]>>=
l->gclink = gcl;
gcl = l;
@
<<[[an()]] add node [[n]] to [[gcl]]>>=
n->gclink = gcl;
gcl = n;
@


<<[[String]] first gc field>>=
Gc;
@
<<[[List]] first gc field>>=
Gc;
@

% why Node Gc field? it's not really runtime value, but
% we want to gc it when finished processed? or because of Value with Code?
<<[[Node]] first gc field>>=
Gc;
@


\section{Symbol table}

% L stands for? Lexical?

%claude:
The [[acid]] interpreter maintains a hash table mapping
names to [[Lsym]] (``lexical symbol'') entries. This is
[[acid]]'s own symbol table, distinct from the target
program's symbol table in [[libmach]]. It stores everything
the interpreter knows: variable values, function definitions,
keyword tokens, builtin function pointers, and complex type
descriptions. At startup, [<varsym()>] populates it with
entries from the target's symbol table, so that typing
[[main]] at the [[acid]] prompt gives the address of [[main]].

%claude:
The two symbol tables are easy to confuse. Here is the
distinction:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lll}
\toprule
                  & {\bf [[libmach]] symbol table} & {\bf [[acid]] symbol table} \\
\midrule
data type         & [[Sym]] (and [[Symbol]])       & [[Lsym]] (in [[hash[]]]) \\
source            & target binary on disk          & built at runtime \\
key               & address                        & name (string) \\
contents          & target's functions, globals    & everything: targets's syms,\\
                  & locals                         & keywords, user vars, fns, types\\
read by           & [<lookup()>], [<getsym()>]    & [<look()>], [<mkvar()>] \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
%
At startup, [[acid]] reads the libmach symbol table (via
[<syminit()>]) and copies each entry into its own [[hash[]]]
table (via [<varsym()>]), so that target program names become
queryable as [[acid]] variables. From that point on, the user
operates on the [[acid]]-side table.

\subsection{Lexical symbols: [[Lsym]]}

%claude:
An [[Lsym]] has a name, a token kind ([[lexval]]---[[Tid]]
for identifiers, keyword tokens for reserved words), and a
current value ([[v]]).
%an optional function body ([[proc]]),
%an optional builtin function pointer, and an optional complex
%type description ([[lt]]).
%The [[hash]] field chains entries
%in the same hash bucket.

<<struct [[Lsym]]>>=
struct Lsym
{
    // ref_own<string>
    char*	name;
    // enum<Token_kind>
    int	lexval;

    // ref_own<Value>
    Value*	v;

    <<[[Lsym]] other fields>>

    // Extra fields
    <<[[Lsym]] extra fields>>

};
@


<<[[Node]] other fields>>=
// option<Lsym>, Some when op = ONAME
Lsym*	sym;
@

<<[[Lsym]] other fields>>=
// option<Node>, Some when symbol is a user-defined acid function
Node*	proc;
@


%XXX
<<[[Lsym]] other fields>>=
Type*	lt;
@

\subsection{Hash table: [[hash]]}

%claude:
Concretely, after loading a target and defining a couple of
user variables, the [[hash[]]] array looks like this (with
[[Hashsize]]~=~128 buckets, separate chaining via the
[[Lsym.hash]] field):
\begin{verbatim}
   hash[]                 buckets (linked via Lsym.hash)
   +-------+
   |   0   |---> nil
   +-------+
   |   1   |---> Lsym{"while", lexval=Twhile} -> nil
   +-------+       (keyword, installed by kinit)
   |  ...  |
   +-------+
   |  17   |---> Lsym{"main", lexval=Tid,     -> Lsym{"x", lexval=Tid,
   +-------+           v=Value{TINT, 0x1020}}        v=Value{TINT, 42}} -> nil
   |  ...  |     (target symbol from varsym)  (user var, from enter)
   +-------+
   |  42   |---> Lsym{"bpset", lexval=Tid,    -> nil
   +-------+           proc=Node{OCALL...}, builtin=bpset_c}
   |  ...  |     (function, both a user-defined proc AND a C builtin)
   +-------+
   |  127  |---> nil
   +-------+
\end{verbatim}
%
Three things are worth noting from this picture. First, the
same bucket holds entries of very different kinds: keywords,
target symbols, user variables, functions---they all share
one flat namespace because [[acid]] is an untyped interpreter
and [[lexval]] is how the lexer decides whether a name tokenises
as [[Tid]] or as a reserved keyword. Second, a single [[Lsym]]
can have \emph{both} a [[proc]] AST and a [[builtin]] pointer,
and at call time the interpreter prefers the user's [[proc]]---this
is how [[/lib/acid/port.acid]] overrides the built-in
[[bpset]] with its own library implementation while keeping
the C version reachable. Third, because the scope of a name
is always the whole table, there is no lexical scoping at the
hash-table level; function locals get their separate stack
mechanism described later.

%claude:
The hash table uses a simple multiplicative hash
([[h = h*3 + *p]]) with separate chaining. [<look()>]
searches for an existing entry; [<enter()>] creates a
new one with a freshly allocated [[Value]] (defaulting
to integer type with hexadecimal format). [<mkvar()>]
combines both: look up first, create if not found.

<<global [[hash]]>>=
// hash <string, ref_own<Lsym>, (next in bucket = Lsym.hash)
Lsym*	hash[Hashsize];
@
<<acid constants>>=
Hashsize	= 128,
@

<<[[Lsym]] extra fields>>=
// list<ref<Lsym>> (next = Sym.hash) bucket of hashtbl 'hash'
Lsym*	hash;
@


<<function [[look]]>>=
Lsym*
look(char *name)
{
    Lsym *s;
    uint h;
    char *p;

    h = 0;
    for(p = name; *p; p++)
        h = h*3 + *p;
    h %= Hashsize;

    for(s = hash[h]; s; s = s->hash)
        if(strcmp(name, s->name) == 0)
            return s;
    // else
    return nil;
}
@

\subsection{Look up or create: [[mkvar()]]}

<<function [[mkvar]]>>=
Lsym*
mkvar(char *s)
{
    Lsym *l;

    l = look(s);
    if(l == nil)
        l = enter(s, Tid);
    return l;
}
@


\subsection{Inserting new symbols: [[enter()]]}

<<function [[enter]]>>=
Lsym*
enter(char *name, int t)
{
    Lsym *s;
    uint h;
    char *p;
    <<[[enter()]] other locals>>

    // dupe of look()?
    h = 0;
    for(p = name; *p; p++)
        h = h*3 + *p;
    h %= Hashsize;

    s = gmalloc(sizeof(Lsym));
    memset(s, 0, sizeof(Lsym));
    s->name = strdup(name);
    s->lexval = t;

    s->hash = hash[h];
    hash[h] = s;

    <<[[enter()]] allocate value of symbol>>

    return s;
}
@


<<[[enter()]] other locals>>=
Value *v;
@

<<[[enter()]] allocate value of symbol>>=
v = gmalloc(sizeof(Value));
s->v = v;

v->fmt = 'X';
v->type = TINT;
memset(v, 0, sizeof(Value));
@
% Hexa fmt by default


\subsection{Builtins}

%claude:
Builtin functions are implemented in C and registered in
the [<tab>] array. During initialization, [<installbuiltin()>]
copies each entry's function pointer into the corresponding
[[Lsym]]'s [[builtin]] field. When [[acid]] encounters a
function call, it checks [[s->builtin]] first---if set (and
no user-defined [[proc]] overrides it), the C function is
called directly rather than interpreting an AST.

<<global [[tab]]>>=
struct Btab
{
    char	*name;
    void	(*fn)(Node*, Node*);
} tab[] =
{
    <<[[tab]] entries>>
    0
};
@


<<[[Lsym]] other fields>>=
void	(*builtin)(Node*, Node*);
@
% will be set by installbuiltin()


%******************************************************************************
\chapter{[[/bin/acid]]}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:acid}

%claude:
This chapter presents [[acid]]'s entry point, REPL,
initialization, and process attachment. The overall flow
is: parse command-line arguments, open the executable,
load symbol tables, load the [[acid]] library files,
then enter the interactive REPL loop.

\section{Entry point: [[main()]]}

<<global [[aout]]>>=
// given program to debug (or /proc/<pid>/text when running acid <pid>)
char*	aout;
@

<<global [[quiet]]>>=
bool	quiet;
@


<<global [[bioout]]>>=
static Biobuf	bioout;
@
<<global [[bout]]>>=
// pointer to bioout
Biobuf*	bout;
@

%claude:
[<main()>] processes command-line flags, determines the executable
and optional PID, then runs a long initialization sequence:
format handlers, keyword table, lexer setup, builtins, symbol
loading, module loading, and the user's [[acidinit]] function.
Finally it enters the infinite REPL loop.

<<function main (acid/main.c)>>=
void
main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
    int pid = 0;
    <<[[main()]](acid) other locals>>

    argv0 = argv[0];
    aout = "8.out";
    quiet = true;
    mtype = nil;

    ARGBEGIN{
    <<[[main()]](acid) command line processing>>
    default:
        usage();
    }ARGEND

    if(argc > 0) {
        <<[[main()]](acid) if argc and remote adjust [[aout]]>>
        else
        <<[[main()]](acid) if [[acid pid]]>>
        else {
            <<[[main()]](acid) if kernel and no pid>>
            aout = argv[0];
        }
    } else
       <<[[main()]](acid) if not argc and remote adjust [[aout]]>>

    <<[[main()]](acid) format initializations>>
    <<[[main()]](acid) initializations>>

    <<[[main()]](acid) infinite loop>>
    /* not reached */
}
@

\section{REPL}


%yoann: explain interactive global before explaining REPL
%claude:
The [[interactive]] global controls whether [[acid]] is reading
from a terminal (the user typing at the [[acid:]] prompt) or
from a file (a library being loaded). When [[interactive]] is
true, [[acid]] prints prompts and a newline ends a statement;
when false, it processes input silently and expects explicit
semicolons to end statements. This is similar to how [[rc]]
distinguishes interactive from script mode.

<<global interactive (acid/globals.c)>>=
bool	interactive;
@
% for prompt essentially, like in rc

%yoann: explain line global
%claude:
The [[line]] global tracks the current line number in the
input source. It is used only for error reporting---when
the lexer or parser fails, the error message includes
[[line]] so the user can find the offending line. The lexer
increments it on every newline.

<<global line (acid/globals.c)>>=
int	line;
@
% for error report


%claude:
The REPL (Read-Eval-Print Loop) is [[acid]]'s interactive
command loop. It prints the [[acid:]] prompt, calls
[<yyparse()>] to parse and execute one statement, then
loops back. An important subtlety: [[yyparse()]] does not
just parse---it also \emph{executes} the parsed statement
immediately (via the [[bigstmnt]] grammar rule, which calls
[<execute()>] inline). So parsing and execution are
interleaved, not separate passes.



<<[[main()]](acid) infinite loop>>=
interactive = true;
line = 1;

for(;;) {
    
    <<[[main()]](acid) in infinite loop, reinit and unwind if error>>
    stacked = 0;

    Bprint(bout, "acid: ");

    // yyparse() will internally call execute() !
    if(yyparse() != OK_1)
        die();
    restartio();

    unwind();
}
@

The [[stacked]] counter tracks brace nesting depth for
multi-line input---when inside braces, [[yylex()]] prints
a tab instead of the prompt.

% ??
<<global [[stacked]]>>=
int	stacked;
@
% for counting {}, also for prompt to show indent so know wait for closing }


%claude:
The REPL uses [[setjmp]]/[[longjmp]] for error recovery:
if any error occurs during parsing or execution, [<error()>]
does a [[longjmp]] back to here, which reinitializes the
output buffer and unwinds any local variable scopes.


<<[[main()]](acid) in infinite loop, reinit and unwind if error>>=
if(setjmp(err)) {
    Binit(&bioout, STDOUT, OWRITE);
    unwind();
}
@
% see error management chapter, for setjmp and unwind


\section{Arguments processing}

\subsection{Quiet mode: [[acid -q]]}

<<[[main()]](acid) command line processing>>=
case 'q':
    quiet = false;
    break;
@


%alt: \subsection{[[acid -m <mtype>]]}
% later

\subsection{Loading extra libraries: [[acid -l <lib>]]}

