%yoann: explain why sproc() directly and no need for newproc(), nproc(), etc. like we saw before
%claude:
Why call [<sproc()>] directly here, instead of going through
[<newproc()>] / [<nproc()>] like we saw earlier for [[new()]]?
Because the [[acid pid]] case attaches to a process that
\emph{already exists}---there is no need to fork or exec.
[<newproc()>] / [<nproc()>] handle the fork/hang/exec dance
required when [[acid]] is starting a fresh program; here,
the target is already running (or [[Broken]]), so we just
need to set up the [[cormap]] for memory access and register
the PID in [[ptab]]. [<sproc()>] does exactly that.


